Plenty could be written about The Bikeriders, the $40 million Austin Butler=
 crime drama that cruised into theaters last weekend and earned a fine-but-=
not-spectacular $10 million. Cue another round of think pieces pondering th=
e viability of midbudget cinema and next-generation movie stars. Yet, behin=
d the scenes, there=E2=80=99s a much stranger story about New Regency, the =
film=E2=80=99s main backer, which is in desperate need of a hit.

For decades, Regency has been a beacon of independent production in Hollywo=
od, churning out critical and commercial blockbusters such as Pretty Woman,=
 Fight Club, Heat, L.A. Confidential, The Big Short, and Gone Girl. But the=
 company=E2=80=99s trajectory angled downward a few years ago when its foun=
der, Arnon Milchan, a billionaire former Israeli spy and
Rupert Murdoch confidant, passed the torch to his son, Yariv. Since then, R=
egency has released a series of flops=E2=80=94The Creator, Amsterdam, Deep =
Water, The Northman=E2=80=94compounded by lawsuits challenging Yariv=E2=80=
=99s management chops.

Adding to the turmoil is a recent case launched by Gavin Polone, the well-k=
nown talent manager turned producer, who=E2=80=99s suing Regency over a sta=
lled movie project, Psycho Killer, which Polone intends to be his directori=
al debut. (The thriller, based on a script by Se7en screenwriter Andrew Kev=
in Walker, was originally slated to be made back in 2009 by Limp Bizkit fro=
ntman Fred Durst.) While the contents of Polone=E2=80=99s litigation are se=
aled in Los Angeles Superior Court, I=E2=80=99ve learned it centers on his =
effort to shop rights to the project to a studio other than Regency. It als=
o paints a picture of a production house sinking under the weight of hundre=
ds of millions of
dollars in recent losses.

Bikeriders might yet help turn the tide for Regency, and for Yariv, who=E2=
=80=99s flying solo while his father, now 79, is tied up abroad as a witnes=
s in Benjamin Netanyahu=E2=80=99s corruption trial. But the production saga=
 behind the movie also suggests that Regency, and Yariv, are in trouble eit=
her way. Bikeriders, directed by Jeff Nichols, was initially destined to be=
 released by Disney=E2=80=99s 20th Century Studios label, before being drop=
ped after its Telluride premiere. Alas, as it turns out, Arnon and Rupert m=
ay have been inseparable from Regency=E2=80=99s success all along.

A Visit From De Niro

The Regency saga began four decades ago with Arnon Milchan=E2=80=99s myster=
ious entry into Hollywood=E2=80=94which has long puzzled the press, since h=
e rarely gives interviews. Milchan, whose past included brokering clandesti=
ne arms deals for Israel, once described ( https://www.independent.co.uk/ne=
ws/world/americas/revealed-arnon-milchan-the-hollywood-producer-behind-hits=
-pretty-woman-fight-club-and-la-confidential-who-became-a-reallife-james-bo=
