9&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da4=
2abd12a ) his younger self as a James
Bond figure. As for how this former Israeli intelligence officer caught his=
 big break, I discovered the answer in a deposition he gave where he recall=
ed getting a serendipitous phone call in the early =E2=80=9980s from Robert=
 De Niro, who was researching a potential film. The actor had heard that Mi=
lchan was connected to Moshe Dayan, a storied Israeli general during the 19=
48 Arab-Israeli War. This prompted a trip to Israel by De Niro and Harvey K=
eitel. Soon after, Jack Nicholson also expressed interest in the film right=
s to Dayan=E2=80=99s story, setting off what Milchan described as =E2=80=9C=
an avalanche of movie stars=E2=80=9D at his door.

Though the Dayan project never materialized, Milchan had gotten a taste of =
Hollywood. In Israel, De Niro showed him the script for The King of Comedy,=
 leading him to become a producer on the Martin Scorsese film. Milchan name=
d his company after the Regency Hotel in New York, where he first set up sh=
op and built
formidable ties with Hollywood=E2=80=99s elite, including Richard Dreyfuss =
and Sydney Pollack. A friendship with Murdoch proved to be one of his most =
significant associations. Murdoch=E2=80=99s 20th Century Fox eventually too=
k a 20 percent stake in Regency, for $200 million, and began distributing m=
any of its films, including Oscar winners 12 Years a Slave, Birdman, and Th=
e Revenant.

But Regency lost a crucial ally when Murdoch sold Fox=E2=80=99s studio asse=
ts to Disney in 2018. Around the same time, Milchan was distancing himself =
from what he now referred to as the =E2=80=9Cstinking ( https://www.hollywo=
odreporter.com/movies/movie-features/a-rare-interview-megaproducer-arnon-90=
4942/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F25%2F24%29&=
