um=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )=
=E2=80=9D movie business, passing the
baton to his son. It fell to Yariv Milchan to navigate the choppy waters of=
 a changing industry and preserve the relationship with Disney=E2=80=94a re=
lationship that, at least based on the Bikeriders production saga, has take=
n a turn.

So what happened? Obviously, Disney C.E.O. Bob Iger=E2=80=99s shifting prio=
rities played a role. Major distributors are far less interested in the kin=
d of original films that Regency makes, and Disney is even less interested =
than other studios. Meanwhile, the market for midbudget fare=E2=80=94Regenc=
y=E2=80=99s bread and butter=E2=80=94has also declined.

But there=E2=80=99s also more to the Disney tale, I hear, hidden in redacte=
d portions of the Polone lawsuit. Sources indicate that Regency=E2=80=99s r=
ecent failures have diminished its willingness to take risks, and executive=
s there were unsatisfied with Disney=E2=80=99s projections on the film. Mea=
nwhile, some stakeholders=E2=80=94especially representatives for the talent=
 involved=E2=80=94pushed for a sale of
Bikeriders to a new distributor. In the end, after the film was dropped fro=
m the Disney slate, it was shopped around and eventually picked up by Unive=
rsal=E2=80=99s specialty arm Focus Features.

=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m Best Friends With Rupert=E2=80=9D

Of course, there were signs of trouble for Regency predating the Bikeriders=
 and Polone dramas. In 2017, the indie producer sued Warren Beatty over the=
 legend=E2=80=99s Howard Hughes rom-com biopic Rules Don=E2=80=99t Apply, a=
ccusing Beatty and his cohort of big-time investors=E2=80=94names like Terr=
y Semel, Ron Burkle, and Brett Ratner=E2=80=94of failing to cover the short=
fall in distribution costs after the film tanked. (Beatty directed and star=
red, in his first screen role in 15 years, opposite his wife, Annette Benin=
g.)

Beatty=E2=80=99s $50 million countersuit pulled no punches, accusing Arnon =
Milchan of being distracted from his producer duties by the Netanyahu bribe=
ry scandal and cash flow issues. Beatty blamed Milchan=E2=80=99s negligence=
 for the film=E2=80=99s dismal critical and commercial reception, noting th=
at
he even dozed off during a screening. Beatty was also enraged that the film=
=E2=80=99s marketing and distribution had been handed over to the novice so=
n, Yariv. Arnon, according to Beatty, had personally assured him he=E2=80=
=99d be running the show. Instead, Beatty complained, it was difficult to g=
et Arnon to focus on anything but Israel. =E2=80=9CHe consulted me on many,=
 many matters,=E2=80=9D said Beatty, who has long styled himself a politica=
l animal. =E2=80=9CMany of them were political.=E2=80=9D

The sentiment was echoed by other investors, who attested to the notion tha=
t, as the late Steve Bing put it, =E2=80=9CThe only reason to go to Regency=
 is not Yariv Milchan; It=E2=80=99s Arnon Milchan.=E2=80=9D Brett Ratner wa=
s equally blunt. =E2=80=9CArnon=E2=80=99s pitch always was, you know, =E2=
=80=98Come make a movie with me. =E2=80=A6 I=E2=80=99m best friends with Ru=
pert,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D he testified. =E2=80=9CYour film gets special atten=
tion because of the special relationship he had with the studio.=E2=80=9D

That obviously changed. In 2019, Regency
settled with Beatty, and the buzz around the company faded. Now, however, P=
olone=E2=80=99s suit offers a sequel of sorts to the Beatty case=E2=80=94an=
d another look at whether Regency has anything left in the tank. Although m=
uch of the complaint is secret, sources say it gets into a highly contentio=
us back-and-forth over the final cut of Psycho Killer. In his lawsuit, Polo=
ne implies that racial animus on Yariv=E2=80=99s part might have something =
to do with the firing of one of the film=E2=80=99s editors. (A New Regency =
spokesperson says, =E2=80=9CAny insinuation of racial animosity is absolute=
ly false.=E2=80=9D) Polone, apparently, also claims that Yariv is reneging =
on a deal to allow him to recruit investors to buy out Regency=E2=80=99s ri=
ghts. The case isn=E2=80=99t just a personal feud; it apparently reveals th=
e depths of Regency=E2=80=99s financial troubles, too.

Regency declined to comment on the case, but a person close to the company =
pointed to the success of Bohemian Rhapsody, which grossed $900
million in 2019 and won an Oscar under Yariv=E2=80=99s watch. Additionally,=
 the company has had a modest hit on the television front this year with Am=
azon=E2=80=99s Mr. and Mrs. Smith and has several projects in the works inc=
luding Netflix=E2=80=99s Man on Fire and an Alex Gibney documentary about E=
lon Musk. This source also stressed that the company has all the financing =
it needs for the next few years. In 2023, the investment firm Carlyle close=
d ( https://www.carlyle.com/media-room/news-release-archive/carlyle-provide=
s-175-million-asset-backed-credit-facility-to-new-regency?utm_campaign=3DWh=
at+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F25%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27=
m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F4%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_s=
ource=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) a $175 million loan to =
Regency, which included refinancing existing debt.

As for Arnon Milchan,
he=E2=80=99s now living in Brighton, England, consumed by the Israel-Hamas =
war, as well as the fate of his friend Bibi. Back in 2018, around the time =
of the Beatty suit, the Israeli police recommended charging ( https://www.h=
ollywoodreporter.com/business/business-news/israeli-police-recommend-chargi=
ng-producer-arnon-milchan-prime-minister-bribery-1084390/?utm_campaign=3DWh=
at+I%27m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F25%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27=
m+Hearing%2B+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F4%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_s=
ource=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) Milchan with bribery fo=
r having provided the prime minister with boxes of cigars, crates of champa=
gne, and expensive jewelry, allegedly in exchange for tax advantages. Arnon=
 has avoided prosecution and has become a key witness in the ongoing corrup=
tion trial against Netanyahu, instead.

That=E2=80=99s it for today. A reminder: No What I=E2=80=99m Hearing on Thu=
rsday, see you on Monday.

