x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Of course, there we=
re signs of trouble for Regency predating the <i>Bikeriders</i> and Polone =
dramas. In 2017, the indie producer sued <b>Warren Beatty </b>over the lege=
nd=E2=80=99s <b>Howard Hughes </b>rom-com biopic <i>Rules Don=E2=80=99t App=
ly</i>, accusing Beatty and his cohort of big-time investors=E2=80=94names =
like <b>Terry Semel</b>, <b>Ron Burkle</b>, and <b>Brett Ratner</b>=E2=80=
=94of failing to cover the shortfall in distribution costs after the film t=
anked. (Beatty directed <i>and</i> starred, in his first screen role in 15 =
years, opposite his wife, <b>Annette Bening</b>.)<br/><br/>Beatty=E2=80=99s=
 $50 million countersuit pulled no punches, accusing Arnon Milchan of being=
 distracted from his producer duties by the Netanyahu bribery scandal and c=
ash flow issues. Beatty blamed Milchan=E2=80=99s negligence for the film=E2=
=80=99s dismal critical and commercial reception, noting that
he even dozed off during a screening. Beatty was also enraged that the film=
=E2=80=99s marketing and distribution had been handed over to the novice so=
n, Yariv. Arnon, according to Beatty, had personally assured him he=E2=80=
=99d be running the show. Instead, Beatty complained, it was difficult to g=
et Arnon to focus on anything but Israel. =E2=80=9CHe consulted me on many,=
 many matters,=E2=80=9D said Beatty, who has long styled himself a politica=
l animal. =E2=80=9CMany of them were political.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>The senti=
ment was echoed by other investors, who attested to the notion that, as the=
 late <b>Steve Bing</b> put it, =E2=80=9CThe only reason to go to Regency i=
s not Yariv Milchan; It=E2=80=99s Arnon Milchan.=E2=80=9D Brett Ratner was =
equally blunt. =E2=80=9CArnon=E2=80=99s pitch always was, you know, =E2=80=
=98Come make a movie with me. =E2=80=A6 I=E2=80=99m best friends with Ruper=
t,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D he testified. =E2=80=9CYour film gets special attentio=
n because of the special relationship he had with the studio.=E2=80=9D <br/=
><br/>That obviously changed. In 2019, Regency
settled with Beatty, and the buzz around the company faded. Now, however, P=
olone=E2=80=99s suit offers a sequel of sorts to the Beatty case=E2=80=94an=
d another look at whether Regency has anything left in the tank. Although m=
uch of the complaint is secret, sources say it gets into a highly contentio=
us back-and-forth over the final cut of <i>Psycho Killer</i>. In his lawsui=
t, Polone implies that racial animus on Yariv=E2=80=99s part might have som=
ething to do with the firing of one of the film=E2=80=99s editors. (A New R=
egency spokesperson says, =E2=80=9CAny insinuation of racial animosity is a=
bsolutely false.=E2=80=9D) Polone, apparently, also claims that Yariv is re=
neging on a deal to allow him to recruit investors to buy out Regency=E2=80=
=99s rights. The case isn=E2=80=99t just a personal feud; it apparently rev=
eals the depths of Regency=E2=80=99s financial troubles, too. <br/><br/>Reg=
ency declined to comment on the case, but a person close to the company poi=
nted to the success of <i>Bohemian Rhapsody</i>, which grossed $900
million in 2019 and won an Oscar under Yariv=E2=80=99s watch. Additionally,=
 the company has had a modest hit on the television front this year with Am=
azon=E2=80=99s <i>Mr. and Mrs. Smith</i> and has several projects in the wo=
rks including Netflix=E2=80=99s <i>Man on Fire</i> and an <b>Alex Gibney</b=
> documentary about <b>Elon Musk</b>.  This source also stressed that the c=
ompany has all the financing it needs for the next few years. In 2023, the =
investment firm Carlyle <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpb=
F9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dRVWZSaHhGdGcxVlFjNW5HWFpBOD0iLCJocmVmIjoi=
